[http://www.flickr.com/photos/32162360@N00]  I have always referred to the whole suspension system as 'catenary'. But a quick 'net search reveals the dilemma! In thirty seconds I sourced three definitions  ... viz:

&quot;A structure built above railroad tracks to carry overhead wire for electric locomotives.&quot;

&quot;A system of wires suspended between poles and bridges supporting overhead contact wires normally energized with electricity.&quot;

&quot;That part of the overhead wiring on electric railways, which hangs between the supporting masts and from which the dropper wires are hung.&quot;

Common usage seems to be that catenary hangs off masts (or poles, or pillars, or pylons ...)

Cheers
